    You enter your username & password
    Spring Security checks it in the database
    If valid â†’ You get access ğŸš€
    If invalid â†’ You see a login error âŒ

2ï¸âƒ£ Authorization (Role-Based Access)

ğŸ”¹ Decides what you can do based on your role

Example:
Role	Can View Users?	Can Edit Users?	Can Delete Users?
Admin	âœ… Yes	âœ… Yes	âœ… Yes
User	âœ… Yes	âŒ No	âŒ No

    Admin can do everything âœ…
    User can only view but not edit/delete âŒ

In Spring Security, we define this using roles like "ROLE_ADMIN", "ROLE_USER".
3ï¸âƒ£ Security Features

âœ… Password Encryption ğŸ”’ (So no one can see raw passwords)
âœ… JWT Authentication ğŸ›¡ï¸ (For token-based login)
âœ… CSRF Protection ğŸ›‘ (Prevents fake form submissions)
âœ… OAuth2 Support ğŸ”‘ (Login with Google, Facebook, etc.)
ğŸ”¹ Simple Spring Security Flow

1ï¸âƒ£ User enters username & password
2ï¸âƒ£ Spring Security checks credentials
3ï¸âƒ£ If valid â†’ User gets access
4ï¸âƒ£ If invalid â†’ Access denied âŒ
5ï¸âƒ£ If user tries to access an admin-only page, Spring Security checks their role
ğŸ”¹ Spring Security in Action

