REST API & RestTemplate Explained Simply
1ï¸âƒ£ What is a REST API?

Imagine you are ordering food from Swiggy/Zomato.

    You (Client) â†’ Open the app and place an order.
    Swiggy (API Server) â†’ Receives the request, talks to the restaurant, and processes your order.
    Restaurant (Database/Backend) â†’ Prepares the food and sends it back via Swiggy.
    You (Client) â†’ Receive the food (response).

Similarly, a REST API allows different applications to talk to each other over the internet using HTTP requests like:
âœ… GET â†’ Fetch data (like checking restaurant menus).
âœ… POST â†’ Send data (like placing an order).
âœ… PUT â†’ Update data (like changing your delivery address).
âœ… DELETE â†’ Remove data (like canceling an order).
2ï¸âƒ£ What is RestTemplate?

Now, imagine you are a Java developer and need to connect to a REST API from your Java application.

    RestTemplate is like the Swiggy App for Developers.
    It helps your Java code send HTTP requests to a REST API and receive responses easily.

ğŸ”¹ Without RestTemplate â†’ You have to write complex code to send API requests manually.
ğŸ”¹ With RestTemplate â†’ You can send API requests in one line and get a response quickly.

ğŸ’¡ Summary:

    REST API = A way for applications to communicate over the internet.
    RestTemplate = A tool in Spring to call REST APIs easily from a Java application.

ğŸ‘‰ Bonus Tip: RestTemplate is now outdated. The newer alternative is WebClient, which is more powerful and recommended for new projects. ğŸ˜Š


